Starting at this point, there is absolutely no way forward towards the sea anymore. We crossed the national park and came from this point onward there is only marsh here, that is impossible to traverse. You should remove that part of the trail.
closing_comment: Thanks for the heads up, and I'm sorry about your inconvenience. I added a tag to that section of the path as a 'seasonal_swamp'. However it's important to note that this and other trails on Bastimentos Island are not standard hiking trails, (nor are they advertised as hiking trails) but access routes used by the locals through the jungles and swamps to go fishing and do other activities. Locals are very used to these conditions, always walking in rubber boots and always carrying a sharp machete in case they need to remove obstacles or clear a path around them; or plain and simple, avoiding these jungle routes altogether if the weather conditions make them impassable, which sounds like it's been the case in the last few months. Thanks again for the notice!

'DON'T GO THERE - unlike you really wanna get robbed. It is like a slum-like dangerous area. I did the mistake, walking along the road and three guys wanted to rob me and my friend. We only walked there because of Google Maps pedestrians navigation which led us through this dangerous area. We wanted to walk from the bus station to Casco Viejo because we had to kill some time. The bus from David has arrived at 3:30am and our flights from Tocumen airport are at 11am respectively at 1pm. When the three boys tried to attack us, there was a taxi passing by. I shouted loud for the taxi several times, but I didn't stop in the first place, maybe because the taxi driver didn't want to get involved in the crime scene. But my taxi shouting got attention by the police and just in one minute 3 police cars and 20 police officers have arrived at the crime scene. A big shoutout for the panamanian police. After that the three criminals escaped back to the inside of their slum and the situation was under control. We talked a little bit to the police officers and after that we took the taxi to Casco Viejo. When we arrived at Casco Viejo, I paid the taxi driver all of my remaining US-Dollars, which has been arround 50 bucks, because probably his appearance saved our lives.'
